WEBVTT

1
00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:38.830
Ben Pfaff: Oh, hello.

2
00:01:40.490 --> 00:01:42.179
Thorin (Joe): Hello, how are you?

3
00:01:42.180 --> 00:01:44.839
Ben Pfaff: I'm… I'm well, I'm well.

4
00:01:46.330 --> 00:01:47.960
Thorin (Joe): Cool, cool, cool.

5
00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:59.849
Ben Pfaff: And yourself, have you rethought the idea of getting a job? I believe you brought that up a while back.

6
00:02:00.460 --> 00:02:01.989
Thorin (Joe): It's too late.

7
00:02:03.840 --> 00:02:07.990
Ben Pfaff: I thought one of us had finally escaped, and there you are, going back into it.

8
00:02:07.990 --> 00:02:13.140
Thorin (Joe): They pulled me back… pulled me back in, so yeah, it's been a couple of weeks now. I'm doing okay with it. It's,

9
00:02:15.640 --> 00:02:17.840
Thorin (Joe): It's not bad, it's just, you know…

10
00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:18.660
Ben Pfaff: It's still…

11
00:02:18.660 --> 00:02:22.540
Thorin (Joe): a job, right? It's like, it's good, I like having something to do.

12
00:02:25.170 --> 00:02:28.880
Thorin (Joe): But… it also involves having a job.

13
00:02:29.460 --> 00:02:33.100
Ben Pfaff: Oh, it must be 6.

14
00:02:53.990 --> 00:02:58.160
Thorin (Joe): Yeah, no, so the… a lot of the team is in Europe, we're on the East Coast.

15
00:02:58.510 --> 00:03:00.069
Thorin (Joe): mostly Europe, and so…

16
00:03:00.070 --> 00:03:01.410
Ben Pfaff: That's a normal thing.

17
00:03:02.950 --> 00:03:09.850
Thorin (Joe): Well, yeah, except for the fact that, like, that means that I have all these meetings that are at some ungodly hour in the morning.

18
00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:11.940
Ben Pfaff: Oh, alright.

19
00:03:12.460 --> 00:03:17.270
Ben Pfaff: They, they expect you to be up at 6, or worse.

20
00:03:17.490 --> 00:03:19.399
Thorin (Joe): I mean… yeah.

21
00:03:20.010 --> 00:03:24.480
Thorin (Joe): It's not, I mean, so… It's more like…

22
00:03:26.170 --> 00:03:32.659
Thorin (Joe): you know, nobody expects me to, but also, it would be weird if I didn't, because I'm, like, CTO.

23
00:03:33.090 --> 00:03:35.829
Thorin (Joe): So… I don't know.

24
00:03:38.390 --> 00:03:40.530
Thorin (Joe): But I'm trying to, like… I'm trying to, like…

25
00:03:41.150 --> 00:03:46.729
Thorin (Joe): make my role be, like, I get to do a bunch of stuff, but nobody holds me accountable for anything?

26
00:03:46.730 --> 00:03:48.280
Ben Pfaff: Oh, well, that sounds great.

27
00:03:48.540 --> 00:03:58.370
Thorin (Joe): Well, but, I mean, the truth of the matter is, part of my role is that I get pulled in a gazillion different directions, so if I… you put me on critical path for anything, there's a good chance, like, something's gonna come up and I won't be able to do it, so…

28
00:04:00.200 --> 00:04:02.489
Thorin (Joe): I don't know. That's my excuse, at least.

29
00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:06.389
Mike Hall: That's always a problem.

30
00:04:07.850 --> 00:04:11.949
Thorin (Joe): But I did get a PR submitted today, so, you know, there's that.

31
00:04:12.190 --> 00:04:12.950
Ben Pfaff: Oh.

32
00:04:16.450 --> 00:04:17.339
Mike Hall: That's cool.

33
00:04:19.240 --> 00:04:20.190
Mike Hall: You're good.

34
00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:23.350
Gabe: Look.

35
00:04:23.450 --> 00:04:26.299
Ben Pfaff: homework before our vacation. What is this?

36
00:04:32.530 --> 00:04:36.049
Thorin (Joe): So, Gabe, do you actually use the gym equipment, or is it just a really cool background?

37
00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:38.680
Gabe: Every day, I mean, and…

38
00:04:38.680 --> 00:04:45.540
Thorin (Joe): Yeah. Do you… is it while you're on video? Do you, like, you know, do you, like, you know, video yourself and, like, you know…

39
00:04:45.540 --> 00:04:46.159
Mike Hall: You haven't seen it?

40
00:04:46.610 --> 00:04:46.960
Mike Hall: They're.

41
00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:52.589
Thorin (Joe): It turns out he just, like, streams for hours a day, just getting ripped.

42
00:04:52.590 --> 00:04:58.390
Gabe: Yeah, there's this whole Agentic workflow, it does analysis, feedback… Totally, yeah.

43
00:04:58.690 --> 00:05:00.500
Thorin (Joe): So, here's my theory, is that…

44
00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:09.150
Thorin (Joe): you start doing the, you know, the AI coding stuff, right? And you could have, like, 4 different versions of Claude going at the same time.

45
00:05:09.400 --> 00:05:12.230
Thorin (Joe): Or, you could watch a TV show.

46
00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:23.390
Thorin (Joe): And I'm just saying that it used to be that, like, working needed your full attention. Now you can watch a TV show while you're working. Now, I haven't done this, but I'm tempted to try it.

47
00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:29.830
Mike Hall: I mean, I remember back in the day when even an incremental compile might take 15 minutes to link.

48
00:05:29.980 --> 00:05:35.869
Mike Hall: And you could go get a coffee, maybe go talk to some friends in the break room who were also waiting on a compile.

49
00:05:37.230 --> 00:05:50.349
Thorin (Joe): When I first started working on Internet Explorer, I think a full, clean build of the IE codebase took about 8 hours. And so, like, if you were changing header files, you're like, well, there goes my day, right? You would, like, strategize.

50
00:05:50.350 --> 00:05:51.699
Mike Hall: Time to go home.

51
00:05:51.700 --> 00:05:53.740
Thorin (Joe): Do it and go home, right?

52
00:05:53.740 --> 00:06:03.490
Ben Pfaff: Well, my first couple of years at VMware, at least once a day, the file servers would go down, and we'd all just sort of mill around and talk to each other.

53
00:06:03.490 --> 00:06:05.630
Thorin (Joe): GitHub going down, so, you know, you got that going.

54
00:06:06.360 --> 00:06:13.019
Mike Hall: GitHub, never… it'll never go down, it's got 5 nines. You just have to go out, like, 12 decimal places.

55
00:06:13.020 --> 00:06:16.469
Thorin (Joe): The pie has five nines, too, somewhere.

56
00:06:16.470 --> 00:06:17.910
Ben Pfaff: It has plenty of aids.

57
00:06:19.630 --> 00:06:21.940
Kostadis Roussos: Well, give me one second, guys, I need to set up my video.

58
00:06:22.200 --> 00:06:23.430
Mike Hall: Yeah, no worries, Kostadis.

59
00:06:23.430 --> 00:06:33.290
Thorin (Joe): Okay, so, does pi have an infinite number of sequential 9s in it somewhere if you go far enough? Like, how does the, sort of, the infinity work? Is there infinity within the infinity?

60
00:06:33.520 --> 00:06:37.569
Thorin (Joe): Can I say, like, by that definition, pi has an infinite number of nines?

61
00:06:37.570 --> 00:06:43.210
Mike Hall: There is… there is, like, an entire class of numerics and math around.

62
00:06:43.210 --> 00:06:45.449
Thorin (Joe): answer these exact questions, yes.

63
00:06:45.450 --> 00:06:47.480
Mike Hall: The theory for this type of stuff.

64
00:06:47.550 --> 00:06:48.170
Thorin (Joe): Yeah.

65
00:06:48.170 --> 00:06:50.400
Mike Hall: And the short answer is, I don't know.

66
00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:54.230
Thorin (Joe): Well, my understanding is there's, like, different levels of infinity, right?

67
00:06:54.230 --> 00:06:55.720
Ben Pfaff: There are, yeah, yeah, yeah.

68
00:06:56.240 --> 00:06:57.049
Mike Hall: There's, like, an…

69
00:06:57.050 --> 00:07:00.050
Thorin (Joe): Low infinity and fast infinity, I don't fucking know, right?

70
00:07:00.050 --> 00:07:10.179
Ben Pfaff: I think that the number of, the number of natural numbers is the smallest infinity, something like that? Aleph null.

71
00:07:11.210 --> 00:07:15.609
Ben Pfaff: And at that point, you've… I've exhausted what I know.

72
00:07:15.610 --> 00:07:20.800
Thorin (Joe): So you can't answer my question, it's like, can we say that pi has an infinite number of 9s in it?

73
00:07:20.800 --> 00:07:23.079
Ben Pfaff: Oh, sure, we can say that, I say that right now.

74
00:07:23.680 --> 00:07:25.180
Mike Hall: I certainly can't prove it.

75
00:07:26.980 --> 00:07:27.640
Gabe: At all.

76
00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:28.630
Ben Pfaff: that either.

77
00:07:29.640 --> 00:07:31.470
Gabe: Adolo's sequential.

78
00:07:31.790 --> 00:07:32.750
Thorin (Joe): Sequential.

79
00:07:33.080 --> 00:07:36.370
Gabe: Sequential infinite number. I mean, hmm, why…

80
00:07:36.370 --> 00:07:44.589
Ben Pfaff: No, no, if there was a sequential infinite number of nines, then it would all round up to zero, and it would no longer be infinite.

81
00:07:44.590 --> 00:07:45.310
Mike Hall: Right.

82
00:07:45.310 --> 00:07:45.710
Ben Pfaff: And so…

83
00:07:45.710 --> 00:07:49.559
Mike Hall: Yeah, it wouldn't be an irrational, like.

84
00:07:49.560 --> 00:07:50.950
Thorin (Joe): What would be up to that point?

85
00:07:50.950 --> 00:07:51.939
Ben Pfaff: It would have to be…

86
00:07:51.940 --> 00:07:54.899
Thorin (Joe): If they pass that infinity, it actually gets random again.

87
00:07:54.900 --> 00:07:57.510
Ben Pfaff: If it, okay.

88
00:07:57.510 --> 00:07:58.139
Thorin (Joe): But I am.

89
00:07:58.140 --> 00:07:59.310
Ben Pfaff: It would have to be at the end.

90
00:07:59.310 --> 00:08:02.059
Thorin (Joe): 5, 9, somewhere in pi, right?

91
00:08:02.060 --> 00:08:05.320
Mike Hall: Have you seen the movie Contact?

92
00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:06.730
Thorin (Joe): Okay.

93
00:08:06.730 --> 00:08:07.549
Ben Pfaff: Have you been to…

